5","1442":"1442","1430":"1430","about 1365":"about 1365","about 1350":"about 1350","1329":"1329","Dunbartonshire, Scotland":"Dunbartonshire, Scotland","Cromarty, Ross, Scotland":"Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Cumbernauld, , Dunbartonshire, Scotland":"Cumbernauld, Dunbartonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Urchard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Burchett  .","German: variant of   Burkhart  .","History: Thomas Burchard came from London, England, to MA in 1635 aboard the <i>True Love</i>, and by 1652 he was in Edgartown on Martha's Vineyard."],"variants":[{"name":"Burchett","meanings":["English: topographic or habitational name from Middle English <i>birchet</i> ‘birch grove’ (Old English <i>bircet</i>, <i>byrcet</i>), a common element in minor placenames in Sussex and found also in Kent, Surrey, and Essex."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Gaelic equivalent of <b>Adam</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Urquhart","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Ross and Cromarty): habitational name from any of various places in Scotland so called, notably the barony of Urquhart (Inverness), or places in Ross and Cromarty, Morayshire, and Fife. All are thought to derive from Pictish <i>ar</i> ‘on, by’ + Pictish <i>carden</i> ‘enclosure’ or ‘wood, copse’. Some bearers of this name trace their descent from William <i>de Urchard</i>, who fought for Robert the Bruce between 1297 and 1328."],"variants":[{"name":"Orcutt","meanings":["English (Staffordshire): perhaps a much altered form of Scottish   Urquhart  ."]},{"name":"Orchard","meanings":["topographic or occupational name from residence near (or perhaps employment at) an orchard, Middle English <i>orchard</i> (Old English <i>ortgeard</i>, <i>orceard</i>).","habitational name from any of the places called Orchard. Those in Devon and Somerset are named from Old English <i>ortgeard</i>, <i>orceard</i> (a compound of <i>wort</i>, <i>wyrt</i> ‘plant’ (later associated with Latin <i>hortus</i> ‘garden’) + <i>geard</i> ‘yard, enclosure’), while East and West Orchard near Shaftesbury in Dorset derive from Primitive Welsh <i>ar</i> ‘beside, in front of, facing’ + <i>ced</i> ‘wood’.","rare variant of Scottish   Urquhart  . Compare   Orahood  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adam Urquhart de Urchard 2nd of Cromarty, Sheriff of Cromarty was born about 1350, his father, William Urquhart de Urchard 1st of Cromarty, Sheriff of Cromarty, was 26 and his mother, Lillias De Ross, was 22. He married Lady Brigida Fleming about 1367, in Cumbernauld, Dunbartonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died about 1385, at the age of 37."},"et":{"about 1350–abt 1385":"umbes 1350–umbes 1385","1284–Female":"1284–Surnud","1350–1385":"1350–1385","1360–1413":"1360–1413","1360–1430":"1360–1430","1360–1442":"1360–1442","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1368–1425":"1368–1425","1325–1395":"1325–1395","1329–1366":"1329–1366","1